		  <td width="135" class="forum_boardrow2" style="border-width: 0px 0px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="messageuser30572887" style="padding-bottom: 2px;"><a href="/profile/Kuiper"><strong>Kuiper</strong></a></div>
		  
		  <a href="/profile/Kuiper"><img src="http://cdn.myanimelist.net/images/useravatars/331692.png" vspace="2" border="0"></a>
		  <br>
		  Offline<br>
		  Joined: May 2010<br>
		  Posts: 74
		  </td>
		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message30572887">I think twinbells nailed the main discussion points.  To add, I think that there are anime which require certain social contexts to enjoy--social contexts that no longer exist.<br />
<br />
I'd like to point toward the example of Evangelion.  To really appreciate it, you need to come at it from the perspective of a native Japanese person who was raised on super robot anime (culturally ubiquitous in the decades that preceded it) and participating in a society that was experiencing a very real economic decline that manifested itself most potently toward the end of the 1980's and became an undeniable reality for a generation in the 90's.<br />
<br />
Evangelion was deconstructive in the way that it broke down the tropes associated with the super robot anime genre, but even more than that, it had its original broadcast run in 1995, smack dab in the middle of Japan's [url=http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lost_Decade_(Japan)]Lost Decade[/url].  An economic empire was crumbling to its knees.  And for the people feeling the effects of that, consider what Evangelion represented: it was the brainchild of a clinically depressed director, a story about the end of the world.  And it hit home in a really big way.  The cultural impact of Evangelion as an anime is truly second to none.<br />
<br />
There are certain elements of Evangelion that have a certain timelessness to them.  Teenage angst and themes of depression will certainly never become obsolete.  But it's simply impossible to recreate those transient viewing conditions that existed at a very specific point in Japanese history.  For me, it's interesting to watch Evangelion and view it from the detached, clinical perspective, looking in as an outside viewer examining the machinations of a director's depression scrambling on a week to week basis to put out a reel for broadcast.  But I will never be that original audience.<br />
<br />
<br />
Remember that culture is defined by time as well as location.  Even contemporary Japanese youths will never experience Astro Boy "as intended," because they are not living their days during the 1960's.  That's not to say that these works can't still be enjoyable on a multitude of levels, but as the discussion title says, "this anime was (not) made for you."</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
