		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message30575669">+++++1 to Kuiper (and of course twinbells for an awesome topic). I couldn't say it better. The influence is irreplaceable.<br />
<br />
That said, one should still hold his/her own opinions, regardless of whether "this anime was (not) made for [them]." It's important as a viewer to keep in mind such things and how culturally sensitive personal judgments may be. It's not always possible to experience the work as it is meant to be experienced (already assuming that there is a "particular way") but it shouldn't stop you from judging the work as you are experiencing it now.<br />
<br />
Perhaps the best compromise is to accomodate as much as physically possible the raw moment. For example, from the obvious to the increasingly inconvenient: watch first seasons before sequels, watch mainstream anime before Lucky Star, follow Cardcaptor Sakura episodes on a weekly schedule, see Akira for the first time in a movie theater with hundreds of (jp) fans, watch anime without subtitles, become a Japanese college dropout who would rather spend the day curled up in bed than face the fear of judgment (to watch NHK). After all, this is just about the best we can do. Or so I think?</div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig"><div style="text-align: center;"><!--link--><a href="http://myanimelist.net/clubs.php?cid=40791">QD</a><!--center--></div></div></td>
